Fruits 360 is

Perfect to have fun

Features 🍊¶

  • Each fruit image has a resolution of 100x100 pixels ( JPG format )
  • Labels for each fruit image, indicating the type of fruit

Number of classes¶

131 different fruit classes in the dataset, which means that there are 60 different types of fruits

Number of fruit classes: 131

🍒 Number of objects per class¶

The number of objects per class varies depending on the fruit type. Some fruits have more images in the dataset than others. For example, there are over 984 images of Grape Blue , while there are only around 492 images of apricots.

Apricot: 492
Grape Blue: 984

Range 🍌🍌¶

The range of the target variable is determined by the number of classes in the dataset, which is 131.

The target variable is a categorical variable ( 131 possible values ) each corresponding to a different fruit class. The values of the target variable are represented as integers in the range of 0 to 130 ( indices of the class labels in the list of class names )

For example if the class names are stored in a list called class_names, the target variable for an apple image would be 0, while the target variable for a banana image would be 15, assuming that the class name "apple" has index 0 and the class name "banana" has index 15 in the class_names list.

🥧 Limits¶

One potential limit of this dataset is that it only includes images of fruits, which means that the image recognition model trained on this dataset may not perform as well on images of other objects.

Additionally, the dataset does not include any information about the ripeness or quality of the fruit, which could be important information for some use cases.

Finally, the resolution of the images may not be sufficient for some applications, depending on the use case.
